    pearls: ["Prolonged fetal bradycardia is the MOST COMMON and often the FIRST sign of uterine rupture — any bradycardia during TOLAC must be treated as rupture until proven otherwise","Prior classical (vertical) cesarean scar has a 4-9% rupture risk — TOLAC is CONTRAINDICATED; only prior low-transverse scars are candidates for TOLAC (0.2-0.7% risk)","Misoprostol and dinoprostone are ABSOLUTELY CONTRAINDICATED in TOLAC patients — prostaglandins dramatically increase rupture risk beyond acceptable safety margins","Complete rupture (through serosa) causes fetal extrusion into the peritoneal cavity and carries much higher fetal mortality than incomplete rupture (dehiscence)","Decision-to-delivery time of <15-18 minutes is the goal for suspected uterine rupture — this requires proactive preparation for all TOLAC patients","Vaginal bleeding may be deceptively minimal because hemorrhage often occurs intraperitoneally — do NOT be reassured by minimal external bleeding in a patient with other signs of rupture","Short interpregnancy interval (<18 months after cesarean) increases rupture risk because scar tissue has insufficient time for adequate healing and remodeling","Every TOLAC patient should deliver in a facility with 24/7 capability for immediate cesarean delivery, anesthesia, and blood transfusion"],
    quiz: [
      {
        question: "A patient undergoing TOLAC with oxytocin augmentation develops sudden severe abdominal pain and fetal heart rate drops to 80 bpm. Which action should the NP take FIRST?",
        options: ["Increase the oxytocin to strengthen contractions and expedite delivery","Discontinue oxytocin, administer terbutaline, and prepare for emergency cesarean delivery","Perform an amniotomy to reduce intrauterine pressure","Administer misoprostol vaginally to hasten cervical dilation"],
        correct: 1,
        rationale: "The presentation (sudden pain + prolonged fetal bradycardia during TOLAC) is classic for uterine rupture. The immediate action is to stop oxytocin (which increases intrauterine pressure), administer terbutaline to halt contractions, and prepare for emergency cesarean. Increasing oxytocin or using misoprostol would worsen the rupture. Amniotomy delays definitive treatment."
      },
      {
        question: "Which patient is the BEST candidate for trial of labor after cesarean (TOLAC)?",
        options: ["Patient with one prior low-transverse cesarean scar, singleton pregnancy at 39 weeks","Patient with prior classical cesarean incision and current spontaneous labor","Patient with two prior cesarean deliveries and a short interpregnancy interval of 10 months","Patient with prior myomectomy where the uterine cavity was entered"],
        correct: 0,
        rationale: "TOLAC is safest in patients with one prior low-transverse cesarean scar (0.2-0.7% rupture risk). Prior classical incision carries a 4-9% rupture risk and is an absolute contraindication. Multiple prior cesareans and short interpregnancy intervals increase risk. Prior myomectomy with cavity entry creates scar tissue with significant rupture risk."
      },
      {
        question: "An NP is counseling a patient about VBAC. The patient had a prior cesarean with a low-transverse incision 12 months ago. Which factor most increases this patient's risk of uterine rupture?",
        options: ["The patient's age of 32 years","The short interpregnancy interval of 12 months","The patient's BMI of 28","The patient's history of one prior vaginal delivery before the cesarean"],
        correct: 1,
        rationale: "A short interpregnancy interval (<18-24 months) is a significant risk factor for uterine rupture because the cesarean scar has not had adequate time for complete healing and remodeling. Age of 32, BMI of 28, and a prior vaginal delivery (which actually improves VBAC success rates) are not significant rupture risk factors."
      },
    ]
